            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility"> ¶ I would advise that seeds of the Blue Gum tree be sown experimentally if the soil is deep and pervious there, as nothing grows quicker. If high shelter is wanted, other eucalypts also might be trie...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">96.08.00d</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To the Leader</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Letter not found. The text given here is from 'Answers to correspondents’, <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Leader</seg>, 29 August 1896, p. 5 (B96.08.04). It is introduced by '<seg style="font-variant: small-caps; ">Trees Suitable for Breakwind</seg>
                     <seg style="">.— J. R., Muskerry.— On this subject Baron von Mueller writes:'.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I would advise that seeds of the Blue Gum tree be sown experimentally if the soil is deep and pervious there, as nothing grows quicker. If high shelter is wanted, other eucalypts also might be tried, or the Black and the Silver Wattle seeds; these are all cheaply purchasable in Melbourne. With regard to conifers, the <name key="Pinus%20insignis">Pinus insignis</name> is the quickest of all in growth. Pinaster<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Error for</seg> 'P. pinaster and'?</p>
               </note> P. Haleppensis<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     </seg>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">P. halepensis</seg>
                     <seg style="">?</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> grow also comparatively fast and would finally yield turpentine. P. pinea bears edible nuts though they<seg style=""> are small. Gleditischias are also recommendable, and have the advantage of being protected by their long and ramified thorn. Seedlings, which if planted mean gaining one year, can be obtained in most plant nurseries. Elms, Poplars and the British Oak grow also with comparative rapidity, but like the Gleditschias are out of accord for mass planting in the evergreen zone of vegetation here, as they are leafless for nearly half a year. If the soil is moist, the Weeping Willow is capital. The ordinary orchard trees could also be chosen and would soon afford fruits. If the shelter is not required to be very high, then stools of the bamboo reed could be planted, which within some few months would produce a copse row.</seg>
            </p>
